Subject: mandibular lateral line
Value: One of eight distinct lateral lines in the 4-day larva. A sensory system on the surface of the fish, consisting of small sensory patches (neuromasts) distributed in discrete lines over the body surface. The lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance. (See Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)

Value: A strut of cartilage  extending dorsally from the basal plate and with other similar cartilages forming the sides of the brain case. The pila antoptica is posterior to pila metoptica together with which it may enclose the foramen for the ocular motor nerve and opthalmica magna artery.

Subject: villosities
Value: Small hair or nipple like projection on the integument.

Value: A large distinctive organelle aggregate comprised of mitochondria found in developing oocytes of many species. From Pepling et al. 2007.

Value: Part of the fin consisting of flattened epidermal cells elevated into a keel-like structure.

Subject: obsolete ventral ramus of occulomotor nerve

Value: The caudal fin is the most posterior median fin. It is composed of a complex of modified centra and modified neural and hemal arches and spines.

Subject: ischial peduncle
Value: Bony projection (peduncle) that is located on the posterior portion of the ilium, posterior to the acetabulum.

Subject: intertrochanteric fossa
Value: Depression on the ventreal side of the femoral head. Associated with the pubioischiofemoralis externus muscle.

Subject: astragalus-calcaneum unit
Value: Osteological unit consisting of the astragalus and calcaneum.

Subject: cleithrum head
Value: Expanded dorsal region of the cleithrum.

Subject: astragalo-calcaneal canal
Value: The astragalo-calcaneal canal forms a foramen between the articulated astragalus and calcaneum when the canal is ossified (Nesbitt, 2011).

Subject: bicipital crest
Value: Anatomical projection that is an expansion on the proximal region of the humerus.

Subject: obsolete posterior iliac process
Value: Distinct posterior most of the two 'double heads' of the blade of the ilium.

Subject: latissimus dorsi process
Value: A bony process on the dorsal side of the proximal region of the humerus which corresponds to the insertion site of the Latissimus dorsi muscle.

Subject: metacarpal extensor pit
Value: Pits located on the proximodorsal part of metacarpals denoting the attachemnt sites for ligaments.

Subject: prepelvic fin spine
Value: Spine located anterior to the pelvic fin and posterior to the pectoral fin.

Subject: prepectoral space
Value: A triangular, anteroventrally facing area developed between the preaxial margin of the humerus and the proximal limb of the ventral humeral ridge. Based on Callier et al. 2009

Subject: pubic peduncle
Value: Bony projection on the anterior portion of the ilium, anterior to the acetabulum that articulates with the pubis.

Subject: pubis-ischium contact
Value: Contact zone between the pubis and the ischium.

Subject: puboischiadic plate
Value: A broad expnase of bone incorperating both the pubis and the ischium. Origin site for ventral limb muscle including the pubioishciofemoralis externus. Modified from Romer 1956

Subject: palatoquadrate element
Value: Endochondral element that is part of the suspensorium sometimes ossifying distally as the quadrate bone and linking the basal section of the braincase to the lower jaw.

Subject: semilunate carpal
Value: The moon shaped fusion of distal carpals 1 and 2 found in some theropod dinosaurs, permitting greater wrist mobility.

Subject: astragalus head
Value: The region of the astragalus/ talus that carries the articular surface for the navicular.

Subject: entepicondyle fossa
Value: A fossa on the distal humerus proximal to the entepicondyle.

Subject: intercentrum
Value: The anteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).

Subject: pleurocentrum
Value: The posteriormost of the two possible elements found in the tetrapod centrum (when the centrum is not a single element).

Subject: incisor process
Value: Process that is part of the mandible that is in close proximity to the incisor teeth.

Subject: humeral facet on the ulna
Value: Facet on the ulna for articulation with the ulnar condyle of the humerus.

Subject: humeral facet on radius
Value: Facet on the radius for articulation with the radial condyle of the humerus.

Subject: external rim of the coracoid foramen
Value: the external wall of the rim denoting the coracoid foramen.

Subject: tibial facet of femur
Value: Facet on the femur for the tibia.

Subject: musculotendinous bundle
Value: A collection of muscle and tendinous tissue.

Subject: scapulohumeralis muscle
Value: Muscle found primarily in basal sarcopterygians that runs between teh scapulocoracoid and the humerus. Its exact homologies with more derived shoulder muscles in Tetrapoda is unclear.

Subject: anteroventral process of cleithrum
Value: A ramus of the celithrum that descend along the girdle. Its rounded outer surface forms the articulation surface for the clavicle while its anterior surface overlaps with the anterior process of the scapulocoracoid.

Subject: dorsal clavicular process
Value: A process, extending dorsally from the clavicular plate, that attaches to the cleithrum. Modified from Clack 2012 and Coates 1996.

Subject: obsolete maxillary saddle
Value: A fossa that is a depression in the proximal end of the maxilla involved in articulation with the palatine. [Baldwin, CC and Johnson GD. 1996. Interrelationships of Aulopiformes. Pages 355-404 in MLJ Stiassny, LR Parenti, and DG Johnson, (eds.), Interrelationships of fishes. Academic Press, San Diego, CA.]

Subject: urodermal bone
Value: Paired, thin dermal bones at the rear of the caudal fin skeleton, derived from scales.

Subject: aphakic space
Value: The space in the pupil, which is not occupied by the lens. A rostral aphakic space may enhance the forward binocular field of vision.

Subject: anterolateral plate
Value: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderm fishes.

Subject: posterior dorsolateral plate
Value: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms.

Subject: anterior ventrolateral plate
Value: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms.

Subject: posterior ventrolateral plate
Value: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms.

Subject: Y bone
Value: The y bone is a detached neural spine anterior to the haemal spines of preural centrum 2.

Subject: ectocoracoid bone
Value: A paired dermal bone in Gasterosteiformes connected with the coracoid and extending posteriorly. Has also been applied to the element below the scapula and applied to the coracoid in Dipnoi. Dictionary of Ichthyology.

Subject: lepidotrichial segment
Value: Zone of bone organ that is part of a lepidotrich and connected to other segments by collagen fibers. These segments lend flexibility to the lepidtrich.

Subject: pelvic sucking disc
Value: An adhesive disk modified from the pelvic fins in, for example, clingfishes (Gobiesocidae), gobies (Gobiidae) and snailfishes (Liparidae).

Subject: glenoid region
Value: < Region surrounding the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid. [PHENOSCAPE:AD]>

Subject: upper jaw symphyseal region
Value: < The region of the upper jaw on or near the midline. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]>

Subject: ceratotrichium
Value: Elastoidin fin ray that is thickened, generally unbranched and found in the fins of Chondrichthyes.

Subject: predorsal scale
Value: Scale that is part of row along the midline between the dorsal fin and the back of the skull. In counting, all scales crossing the midline are included. (Fishbase)

islet of Langerhans
Value: the clusters of hormone-producing cells that are scattered throughout the pancreas

Subject: feather
Value: one of the epidermal growths that form the distinctive outer covering, or plumage, on birds. Feathers are formed in tiny follicles in the epidermis, or outer skin layer, that produce keratin proteins.

Subject: serous membrane
Value: multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

Subject: stemma
Value: eye-spots which may be set into a pit to reduce the angles of light that enters and affects the eyespot, to allow the organism to deduce the angle of incoming light

Subject: spherical lensed eye
Value: simple eye that consists of a lens of one refractive index

Subject: simple eye with multiple lenses
Value: simple eye that has two or more lenses. Some marine organisms bear more than one lens; for instance the copeopod Pontella has three. The outer has a parabolic surface, countering the effects of spherical aberration while allowing a sharp image to be formed. Copilla's eyes have two lenses, which move in and out like a telescope

Subject: urethra
Value: the fibromuscular tubular canal through which urine is discharged from the bladder to the exterior via the external urinary meatus; in males, the urethra is joined by the ejaculatory ducts and serves as a passageway for semen during ejaculation, as well as a canal for urine during voiding; in females, the urethra is shorter and emerges above the vaginal opening

Subject: trophoblast
Value: the mesectodermal cell layer arising from the trophectoderm that erodes the uterine mucosa and contributes to the formation of the placenta

Subject: blastocele
Value: fluid-filled central region of a blastocyst.

Subject: post-embryonic stage
Value: stage succeeding embryo, including mature structure

Subject: cardiac neural crest
Value: portion of neural crest that develops from the dorsal neural tube. It overlaps the vagal neural crest and migrates to populate the pharyngeal arches 3, 4 and 6 (producing structures in the head) and to the heart, forming connective tissue that separates the great vessels of the heart. [Wikipedia]

Subject: blastopore
Value: the orifice of invagination of the endomesodermal cells during the embryonic stages of an organism.

Subject: lung connective tissue
Value: the connective tissue located between the respiratory (airway and alveolar) epithelium, the capillary endothelium and pleural mesothelium; it contains basement membrane composed of collagen, elastin, proteoglycans, and fibronectin

Subject: facial nucleus
Value: the group of motor neurons residing in the pons that innervate the muscles of facial expression

Subject: olivary body
Value: prominent oval structure in the medulla oblongata, present in pairs, the lower portion of the brainstem. They contain the olivary nuclei

Subject: embryonic cloaca
Value: endoderm-lined chamber that develops as pouch-like dilation of the caudal end of the hindgut and receives the allantois ventrally and two mesonephric ducts laterally; caudally it ends blindly at the cloacal membrane formed by the union of proctodeal (anal pit) ectoderm and cloacal endoderm, with no intervening mesoderm[MP].

Subject: primitive urogenital sinus
Value: the ventral part of the cloaca remaining after septation of the rectum, which further develops into part of the bladder, part of the prostatic part of the male urethra and the urethra and vestibule in females

Subject: tetrapod frontal bone
Value: the bone forming the forehead and roof of the eye orbit

Subject: amnion
Value: the thin innermost layer of the extraembryonic membranes that contains the amniotic fluid; the membrane forms a closed sac in which the embryo and later, the fetus, is suspended and protected

Subject: extensor muscle
Value: a skeletal muscle whose contraction extends or stretches a body part.

Subject: yellow bone marrow
Value: bone marrow in which the fat cells predominate in the meshes of the reticular network.

Subject: parenchyma
Value: functional part of an organ in the body. This is in contrast to the stroma, which refers to the structural tissue of organs, being exactly, connective tissues.

Subject: renal medulla
Value: the inner portion of the kidney consisting of the renal pyramids

Subject: flexor muscle
Value: a skeletal muscle whose contraction bends a joint.

Subject: syncytiotrophoblast
Value: extraembryonic cells of trophoblastic shell surrounding embryo, outside the cytotrophoblast layer, involved with implantation of the blastocyst by eroding extracellular matrix surrounding maternal endometrial cells at site of implantation, also contribute to villi. (dark staining, multinucleated).

Subject: urinary bladder detrusor smooth muscle
Value: bundles of smooth muscle fibers forming the muscular wall of the urinary bladder, which are arranged in a longitudinal and a circular layer and, on contraction, serve to expel urine[MP].

Subject: meniscus
Value: crescent-shaped fibrocartilaginous structure present in the knee, acromioclavicular, sternoclavicular, and temporomandibular joints[2] that, in contrast to articular disks, only partly divides a joint cavity.[3] A small meniscus also occurs in the radio-carpal joint.

Subject: mandibular ramus
Value: the upturned perpendicular extremity of the mandible

Subject: visual cortex
Value: the part of the cerebral cortex responsible for processing visual information.

Subject: major vestibular gland
Value: the paired glands located slightly posterior and to the left and right of the opening of the vagina in the superficial perineal pouch in females; they secrete mucus to lubricate the vagina and are homologous to bulbourethral (Cowper's) glands in males

Subject: hippocampal commissure
Value: the triangular subcallosal plate of commissural fibers resulting from the converging of the right and left fornix bundles which exchange numerous fibers and which curve back in the contralateral fornix to end in the hippocampus of the opposite side

Subject: imaginal disc
Value: one of the parts of a holometabolous insect larva that will become a portion of the outside of the adult insect during the pupal transformation.

Subject: obsolete intestine muscle
Value: intestinal muscle cell, attach to intestine and body wall anterior to anus

Subject: cornea
Value: the transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

Subject: ovary
Value: the gonad of a female organism which contains germ cells

Subject: uterus
Value: the female muscular organ of gestation in which the developing embryo or fetus is nourished until birth

Subject: mammalian vulva
Value: external genital organs of the female mammal[WP].

Subject: cuticle
Value: tough but flexible, non-mineral outer coverings of an organism, or parts of an organism, that provide protection. Cuticles are non-homologous, differing in their origin, structure and chemical composition[WP].

Subject: circulatory system
Value: organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc. to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis[WP].

Subject: saliva-secreting gland
Value: saliva-secreting exocrine glands of the oral cavity[GO]

Subject: rectum
Value: the terminal portion of the intestinal tube, terminating with the anus

Subject: flocculus
Value: the small lobe of the cerebellum at the posterior border of the middle cerebellar peduncle anterior to the biventer lobule that receives input from the inferior and medial vestibular nuclei and sends fibers back to the vestibular nuclei, and processes and integrates these signals to allow for the constant maintenance of balance

Subject: pedicle of vertebra
Value: the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the body to the laminae

Subject: axillary lymph node
Value: the lymph nodes located around the axillary vein that receive lymphatic drainage from the upper or forelimb, scapular region and pectoral region

Subject: intercostal muscle
Value: the respiratory muscles that arise from the lower border of one rib and insert into the upper border of the adjoining rib

Subject: cystic duct
Value: the tubular structure that conducts gall bladder contents from the gall bladder to the common bile duct

Subject: pyloric antrum
Value: the area at the bottom of the stomach on the caudal side of the pyloric canal that contains gastrin-producing G cells, which stimulate acid production, and the luminal pH-sensitive population of somatostatin-producing D cells

Subject: pylorus
Value: the stomach tissue region surrounding and controlling the distal outlet of the stomach, which opens into the duodenum

Subject: wall of stomach
Value: the layered structure that makes up the stomach, typiclly consists of a serous coat, a muscular coat, a mucous membrane, and other tissue layers in between

Subject: common bile duct
Value: the part of the biliary tree formed by the union of the cystic duct and the common hepatic duct

Subject: submucosa of stomach
Value: the fibrous connective tissue layer beneath the stomach mucosa

Subject: serosa of stomach
Value: the outermost layer of the stomach wall, consisting of layers of connective tissue continuous with the peritoneum

Subject: muscularis mucosae of stomach
Value: the thin layer of smooth muscle in the mucosal layer of the stomach that functions to agitate the surface area stomach mucosa by moving the villi back and forth

Subject: submucosa of small intestine
Value: submucosal tissue in the small intestines.

Subject: Peyer's patch
Value: the protruding lymphoid tissue located on the mucosa of the intestine that is composed of densely packed B cell follicles

Subject: intestinal villus
Value: the tiny hair-like projections that protrude from the inside of the small intestine that contain blood vessels that capture digested nutrients that are absorbed through the intestinal wall; the villi increase the absorptive surface area of the small intestine by approximately 30-fold

Subject: major calyx
Value: portion of the urinary collecting system within the kidney that drains several minor calyces

Subject: minor calyx
Value: portion of the urinary collecting system within the kidney that drains one renal papilla

Subject: renal corpuscle
Value: the structure containing the glomerular capsule and the glomerulus that serves as the initial blood-filtering component of a nephron

Subject: adrenal cortex
Value: the thick outer layer of the adrenal gland that produces and secretes steroid hormones such as corticosterone, estrone and aldosterone

Subject: adrenal medulla
Value: the inner portion of the adrenal gland that consists mainly of chromaffin cells which produce, store and secrete neurotransmitters such as epinephrine and norepinephrine

Subject: crypt of Lieberkuhn of small intestine
Value: the tubular intestinal glands found in the mucosal membranes of the small intestine

Subject: internal anal sphincter
Value: the smooth muscle ring, formed by an increase of the circular muscle fibers of the rectum, situated at the upper end of the anal canal, internal to the outer voluntary external anal sphincter

Subject: red pulp of spleen
Value: the parenchymatous tissue network of the spleen that consists of loose plates or cords (sinuses) infiltrated with red blood cells where most of the blood filtration occurs and degenerate erythrocytes are removed from the circulation

Subject: marginal zone of spleen
Value: the zone between the red and white pulp of the spleen containing numerous macrophages and lymphocytes, and a rich plexus of sinusoids supplied by white pulp arterioles carrying blood-borne antigens

Subject: urinary bladder
Value: distensible musculomembranous organ situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion[MP].

Subject: trigone of urinary bladder
Value: the smooth triangular region of the wall of the urinary bladder formed by the two ureteral orifices and the internal urethral orifice; it is an area in which the muscle fibers are closely adherent to the mucosa

Subject: mucosa of urinary bladder
Value: the mucous membrane lining the urinary bladder

Subject: intralobular bile duct
Value: the tubules located between the bile canaliculi and interlobular bile ducts near the outer edge of a classic liver lobule

Subject: loop of Henle
Value: the section of the renal tubule in the kidney medulla with a hairpin bend; consists of a descending limb and an ascending limb, and is situated between the proximal convoluted tubule to the distal convoluted tubule; it functions to reabsorb water and ions from the urine

Subject: descending limb of loop of Henle
Value: the portion of the renal tubule that constitutes the proximal part of the loop of Henle, has low permeability to ions and urea, and is highly permeable to water; it consists of an initial short thick segment lined by low simple cuboidal epithelium and a long thin segment lined by simple squamous epithelium; however, this distinction is not as important physiologically as in the ascending limb, so often the two are treated as one structure

Subject: thick ascending limb of loop of Henle
Value: the distal sub-portion of the ascending loop of Henle which is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium and enters the renal cortex to empty a hypotonic filtrate into the distal convoluted tubule

Subject: endometrium
Value: the glandular mucous membrane lining of the uterine cavity that is hormonally responsive during the estrous/menstrual cycle and during pregnancy

Subject: myometrium
Value: the smooth muscle coat of the uterus, which forms the main mass of the organ and surrounds and supports the endometrium

Subject: glans penis
Value: the conic expansion of the corpus spongiosum that forms the head of the penis

Subject: scrotum
Value: the external sac of skin that encloses the testes. It is an extension of the abdomen, and in placentals is located between the penis and anus.

Subject: epididymis
Value: the elongated structure connected to the posterior surface of the testis that transports, stores, and matures spermatozoa between testis and vas deferens

Subject: germinal epithelium of ovary
Value: layer of simple cuboidal cells covering surface of ovary[WP].

Subject: prostatic urethra
Value: the widest and most dilatable part of the male urethra canal which runs almost vertically through the prostate from its base to its apex, lying nearer its anterior than its posterior surface; this portion of the urethral canal is spindle-shaped, being wider in the middle than at either extremity, and narrowest below, where it joins the membranous portion; it is lined by transitional epithelium and contains in its posterior wall, or floor, the orifices of the prostatic utricle, ejaculatory ducts, and prostatic ducts, collectively known as the seminal colliculus (aka verumontanum)

Subject: spongiose part of urethra
Value: the longest part of the male urethra contained in the corpus spongiosum and extending from the end of the membranous portion to the external urethral orifice; commencing below the inferior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm it passes forward and upward to the front of the symphysis pubis; and then, in the flaccid condition of the penis, it bends downward and forward; while narrow and of uniform size in the body of the penis, it is dilated behind, within the bulb, and again anteriorly within the glans penis, where it forms the fossa navicularis urethrae; the spongy urethra is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium proximally, and by stratified squamous epithelium distally

Subject: radial artery
Value: branch of the brachial artery beginning below the elbow and extending down the forearm around the wrist and into the palm.

Subject: subscapular vein
Value: a vein formed by the confluence of the thoracodorsal and circumflex scapular veins and accompanying the subscapular artery to drain into the axillary vein.

Subject: compact bone tissue
Value: the outer layers of solid, hard bone that covers spongy bone; consists of parallel osteons containing mineral deposits and interstitial lamellae

Subject: navicular bone of pes
Value: the oval-shaped tarsal bone found between the talus and the 3 cuneiform bones

Subject: skin of prepuce of penis
Value: the loose fold of skin that covers the penis

Subject: arch of aorta
Value: the convex portion of the aorta between the ascending and descending parts of the aorta; branches from it include the brachiocephalic trunk, the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery; the brachiocephalic trunk further splits to form the right subclavian artery and the right common carotid artery

Subject: thoracic aorta
Value: the part of the aorta that extends from the origin at the heart to the diaphragm, and from which arises numerous branches that supply oxygenated blood to the chest cage and the organs within the chest

Subject: brachiocephalic artery
Value: the short first aortic arch branch and divides into the right subclavian artery and the right common carotid artery

Subject: vertebral artery
Value: the first branch of the left and right subclavian arteries that merge to form the single midline basilar artery; branches of the vertebral arteries supply the musculature of the neck

Subject: inguinal lymph node
Value: the lymph nodes located in the groin area

Subject: popliteal lymph node
Value: the lymph nodes which drain the legs; contained in the popliteal fossa

Subject: lateral marginal vein
Value: a continuation of the Dorsal venous arch of the foot and is the origin of the short saphenous vein

Subject: medial marginal vein
Value: a continuation of the Dorsal venous arch of the foot and is the origin of the long saphenous vein

Subject: transverse sinus
Value: one of the dural venous sinuses and drains the superior sagittal sinus the occipital sinus and the straight sinus, and empties into the sigmoid sinus which in turn reaches the jugular bulb.

Subject: transverse facial vein
Value: a tributary of the superficial temporal or retromandibular veins, anastomosing with the facial vein.

Subject: occipital bone
Value: the bone at the lower, posterior part of the skull

Subject: temporal bone
Value: <the large, irregular bone located at the base and side of the skull; consists of three parts at birth: squamous, tympanic, and petrous>

Subject: lacrimal bone
Value: the irregularly thin plate that forms part of the medial wall of the orbit behind the frontal process of the maxilla

Subject: jugal bone
Value: the quadrilateral bone that forms the prominence of the cheek

Subject: foramen ovale of skull
Value: one of the larger of the several holes at the base of the skull that transmit nerves through the skull. The foramen ovale is situated in the anterior part of the sphenoid bone, posteriolateral to the foramen rotundum..

Subject: geniculate ganglion
Value: the group of sensory neuron cell bodies associated with the facial nerve (seventh cranial nerve)

Subject: cranial ganglion
Value: the groups of nerve cell bodies associated with the twelve cranial nerves

Subject: nasopharynx
Value: the section of the pharynx that lies above the soft palate

Subject: oropharynx
Value: the portion of the pharynx that lies between the soft palate and the upper edge of the epiglottis

Subject: pharyngeal tonsil
Value: the lymph tissue in the roof and posterior wall of the nasopharynx

Subject: tonsillar ring
Value: the circular lymphoid tissue formed by the lingual, pharyngeal, and facial tonsils

Subject: thyroid cartilage
Value: the largest of the laryngeal cartilages

Subject: arytenoid cartilage
Value: the paired triangular laryngeal cartilages located postlaterally at the level of the thyroid cartilage

Subject: turbinate bone
Value: the small curved bones that extends horizontally along the lateral wall of the nasal passage

Subject: anterior chamber of eyeball
Value: the space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, and bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and part of the crystalline lens

Subject: posterior chamber of eyeball
Value: the ring-like space, filled with aqueous humor, between the iris/pupil anteriorly and the lens and ciliary body posteriorly

Subject: uvea
Value: the pigmented middle of the three concentric layers that make up an eye, consisting of the iris, ciliary body and choroid[WP,edited].

Subject: iris
Value: the adjustable membrane, composed of the stroma and pigmented epithelium, located just in front of the crystalline lens within the eye

Subject: pupil
Value: the central circular aperture of the iris through which light rays enter the eye

Subject: corneal epithelium
Value: the smooth stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea

Subject: ciliary body
Value: the thickened portion of the vascular tunic, which lies between the choroid and the iris, composed of ciliary muscle and ciliary processes

Subject: optic choroid
Value: vascular layer containing connective tissue, of the eye lying between the retina and the sclera. The choroid provides oxygen and nourishment to the outer layers of the retina. Along with the ciliary body and iris, the choroid forms the uveal tract[WP].

Subject: substantia propria of cornea
Value: the lamellated connective tissue of the cornea between the Bowman and Descemet membranes

Subject: spinal nerve
Value: the any of the paired peripheral nerves formed by the union of the dorsal and ventral spinal roots from each spinal cord segment[MP,modified]

Subject: nerve fiber layer of retina
Value: layer of the retina formed by expansion of the fibers of the optic nerve

Subject: anterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in front of, or ventral to, the lens (inclusive)

Subject: posterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in back of, or dorsal to, the lens (but not inclusive)

Subject: capsule of lens
Value: the elastic, clear, membrane-like structure, that is outer most layer of the lens

Subject: autonomic ganglion
Value: ganglion that has dendrites that form a junction between autonomic nerves originating from the central nervous system and autonomic nerves innervating their target organs in the periphery. There are two subtypes, sympathetic ganglion and parasympathetic ganglion.

Subject: conjunctiva
Value: the mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelids and the front of the eyeball

Subject: spinal nerve plexus
Value: an intermingling of fiber fascicles from adjacent spinal nerves to form a network.

Subject: sweat gland
Value: any of the coil glands of the skin that secrete sweat

Subject: paranasal sinus
Value: the paired air-filled cavities surrounded by the bones of the face that are lined by mucous membranes and are continuous with the nasal cavity

Subject: sublingual gland
Value: the small mucin-producing salivary glands in the floor of the mouth beneath the tongue, anterior to the submandibular gland

Subject: cochlea
Value: the spiral-shaped bony canal in the inner ear containing the hair cells that transduce sound. Its core component is the Organ of Corti, the sensory organ of hearing, which is distributed along the partition separating fluid chambers in the coiled tapered tube of the cochlea. [WP,modified].

Subject: auricular cartilage
Value: cartilage of the pinna and much of the external ear canal.

Subject: utricle of membranous labyrinth
Value: the larger of the two otolith organs in the vestibule

Subject: saccule of membranous labyrinth
Value: the smaller of the two otolith organs in the vestibule

Subject: endolymphatic duct
Value: the small membranous canal, connecting with both saccule and utricle of the membranous labyrinth, passing through the aqueduct of vestibule, and terminating in the endolymphatic sac

Subject: scala vestibuli
Value: the division of the spiral canal of the cochlea lying on the apical side of the spiral lamina and vestibular membrane

Subject: scala tympani
Value: the division of the spiral canal of the cochlea lying on the basal side of the spiral lamina

Subject: epithelium of trachea
Value: the epithelial lining of the trachea which contains numerous ciliated cells

Subject: paracentral nucleus
Value: one of the intralaminar nuclei of the thalamus, located medial to the central lateral nucleus.

Subject: lateral geniculate body
Value: the group of neurons that serve as the primary processor of visual information received from the retina via the optic tract and send processed information to the visual cortex of the occipital lobe

Subject: white pulp of spleen
Value: the parenchymatous tissue of the spleen that surrounds splenic blood vessels, consists of compact masses of lymphatic cells and is where foreign material removed from the blood is used to initiate an immune reaction that results in the production of antibodies

Subject: mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue
Value: diffuse system of small concentrations of lymphoid tissue found in various sites of the body such as the gastrointestinal tract, thyroid, breast, lung, salivary glands, eye, and skin[WP]. Mucosal-associated lymphoid tissue is typically found as nodules associated with mucosal epithelia with distinct internal structures including B- and T-zones for the activation of lymphocytes[GO].

Subject: bile
Value: vital aqueous secretion of the liver that is formed by hepatocytes and modified down stream by absorptive and secretory properties of the bile duct epithelium.

Subject: epithelium of esophagus
Value: the epithelial layer that lines the luminal space of the esophagus

Subject: crypt of Lieberkuhn
Value: the tubular intestinal glands found in the mucosal membranes

Subject: placenta
Value: organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin[GO]. The fetal portion of the placenta is known as the villous chorion. The maternal portion is known as the decidua basalis. The two portions are held together by anchoring villi that are anchored to the decidua basalis by the cytotrophoblastic shell.

Subject: middle cervical ganglion
Value: the small ganglion located at the level of the cricoid cartilage of the laryngeal wall

Subject: kidney capsule
Value: the tough fibrous layer surrounding the kidney which is covered in a thick layer of perirenal adipose tissue that functions to provide some protection from trauma and damage

Subject: claustrum of brain
Value: one of the four basal ganglia in each cerebral hemisphere that consists of a thin lamina of gray matter between the lentiform nucleus and the insula[BTO]. The claustrum, which is suspected to be present in all mammals, is a fairly thin (fraction of 1 mm to multiple mms) vertical curved sheet of subcortical gray matter oriented sagittally between the white matter tracts of the external capsule and extreme capsule. The claustrum is lateral to the putamen and medial to the insular cortex and is considered by some sources to be part of the basal ganglia. There are lateral and medial tracts connecting to many cortices and perhaps to the hippocampus, the amygdala, and the caudate nucleus (connections with subcortical centers are a matter of debate)[WP].

Subject: stratum basale of epidermis
Value: the deepest layer of the epidermis, which is composed of dividing stem cells and anchoring cells

Subject: stratum spinosum of epidermis
Value: the layer of polyhedral cells in the epidermis found between the stratum granulosum and stratum basale; shrinkage and adhesion of these cells gives a spiny or prickly appearance

Subject: stratum corneum of epidermis
Value: the outer layer of the epidermis, consisting of several layers of flat keratinized non-nucleated cells

Subject: suprachiasmatic nucleus
Value: * An ovoid densely packed collection of small cells of the anterior hypothalamus lying close to the midline in a shallow impression of the optic chiasm. (MSH) * small group of nerve cell bodies in the supraoptic region of the hypothalamus, just above the optic chiasm; influences rhythmic aspects of hypothalamic functions in many vertebrate species. (CSP)

Subject: adrenal gland capsule
Value: the thick capsule of dense irregular connective tissue that surrounds each adrenal gland and contains scattered elastic fibers; the capsule contains a rich plexus of blood vessels (mainly small arteries) and numerous nerve fibers; some blood vessels and nerves enter the substance of the gland in the trabeculae that extend inward from the capsule and then leave the trabeculae to enter the cortex.

Subject: zona glomerulosa of adrenal gland
Value: the narrow subcapsular outer zone of the adrenal cortex where aldosterone is produced

Subject: zona fasciculata of adrenal gland
Value: the wide middle zone of the adrenal cortex that produces cortisol (hydrocortisone)

Subject: zona reticularis of adrenal gland
Value: the inner zone of the adrenal cortex that produces the enzymes that convert pregnenolone, a 21-carbon steroid, to 19-carbon steroids

Subject: submandibular ganglion
Value: the ganglion associated with the lingual nerve that provides postsynaptic fibers to the submandibular and sublingual glands

Subject: stratum granulosum of epidermis
Value: the layer of flattened cells containing basophilic granules of keratohyalin and lying just above the stratum spinosum (spiny layer) of the epidermis

Subject: cuticle of hair
Value: smooth and glossy outer protective cell layer of hair shaft

Subject: thoracodorsal vein
Value: companion vein of the thoracodorsal artery, draining the apical part of the latissimus dorsi and merging with the circumflex scapular vein to form a subscapular vein

Subject: spleen
Value: the organ that functions to filter blood and to store red corpuscles and platelets

Subject: jejunum
Value: the portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum

Subject: ileum
Value: the portion of the small intestine that extends from the jejunum to the colon

Subject: cortex of thymus
Value: the outer part of a thymus lobule that surrounds the medulla and is composed of closely packed lymphocytes

Subject: inferior olivary complex
Value: largest nucleus situated in the olivary body, part of the medulla oblongata. It is closely associated with the cerebellum, but its specific function is voluntary body movements.

Subject: anterior lobe of cerebellum
Value: the region of the cerebellum that is anterior to the primary fissure

Subject: dentate nucleus
Value: the largest and most lateral of the deep cerebellum nuclei; it receives axons of Purkinje cells in the lateral cerebellar hemisphere (neocerebellum) and receives its afferents from the premotor cortex and the supplementary motor cortex through the pontocerebellar system, and its efferents project through the superior cerebellar peduncle and is a major source of its fibers

Subject: pulmonary valve
Value: the semilunar valve of the heart that lies between the right ventricle and the pulmonary artery.

Subject: fastigial nucleus
Value: the most medial of the cerebellar nuclei; it receives its afferent input from Purkinje cells of the flocculonodular lobe and the vermis, and most of its efferent connections travel via the inferior cerebellar peduncle to the vestibular nuclei and to the medullary reticular formation

Subject: pulmonary alveolar duct
Value: the respiratory conducting tubes distal to the respiratory bronchiole that lead to the alveolar sacs and the alveoli

Subject: bronchus
Value: the upper conducting airways of the lung; these airways arise from the terminus of the trachea

Subject: bronchiole
Value: the conducting airway of the lungs found terminal to the bronchi; these structures contain neither cartilage nor mucous-secreting glands; the epithelium of the bronchioles becomes thinner with each branching

Subject: terminal bronchiole
Value: the last conducting structure of non-respiratory bronchioles; after this point, the airways have alveoli in their walls

Subject: sternebra
Value: one of the bony segments of the sternum[TFD].

Subject: macula of saccule of membranous labyrinth
Value: the oval neuroepithelial sensory receptor in the anterior wall of the saccule; hair cells of the neuroepithelium support the statoconial membrane and have terminal arborizations of vestibular nerve fibers around their bodies

Subject: macula of utricle of membranous labyrinth
Value: the neuroepithelial sensory receptor in the inferolateral wall of the utricle; hair cells of the neuroepithelium support the statoconial membrane and have terminal arborizations of vestibular nerve fibers around their bodies; normally sensitive to linear acceleration in the longitudinal axis of the body and to gravitational influences

Subject: costal cartilage
Value: the nonvascular, resilient, flexible hyaline connective tissue that connects the end of a true rib to the sternum or the end of a false rib with the with the lower border of the costal cartilage above it

Subject: nucleus pulposus
Value: the jelly-like substance in the middle of the spinal disc which is a remnant of the notochord

Subject: cutaneous vein
Value: one of a number of veins in the subcutaneous tissue that empty into deep veins

Subject: uterine horn
Value: either one of the pair of tubular extensions from the uterine body where the uterus and the uterine tubes meet; uterine horns are anterior Mullerian duct-derived structures

Subject: dorsal funiculus of spinal cord
Value: the white substance of the spinal cord lying on either side between the posterior median sulcus and the dorsal root.

Subject: scala media
Value: the division of the spiral canal of the cochlea that contains the organ of Corti (the neuroepithelial receptor organ for hearing)

Subject: myocardium of atrium
Value: the atrial part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle

Subject: nasal mucus
Value: mucus produced in the nasal cavity, by the respiratory segment of the nasal mucosa.

Subject: extraglomerular mesangium
Value: the tissue comprised of mesangial cells that fill the triangular space between the macula densa and the afferent and efferent arterioles of the juxtaglomerular apparatus

Subject: periventricular nucleus
Value: a thin sheet of small neurons located in the wall of the third ventricle, a composite structure of the hypothalamus.

Subject: submandibular duct
Value: the duct of the submadibular gland that opens at the sublingual papilla near the frenulum of the tongue

Subject: epicardium
Value: a region of the serous membrane that forms the innermost layer of the pericardium and the outer surface of the heart.

Subject: myocardium
Value: the middle layer of the heart, comprised mainly of striated cardiac muscle fibers

Subject: bone marrow
Value: the soft tissue that fills the cavities of bones

Subject: tonsil
Value: either of the two small almond-shaped masses of lymph tissue found on either side of the oropharynx

Subject: palatine tonsil
Value: tonsils on the left and right sides at the back of the throat. one of the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues (MALT), located at the entrance to the upper respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts to protect the body from the entry of exogenous material through mucosal sites[WP].

Subject: pes
Value: distal portion of the hind limb, including tarsal region, metatarsal region and digits.

Subject: nasolacrimal duct
Value: the paired channels leading from the lacrimal sacs to the inferior meatus of the nose, through which tears are conducted through the nasal cavity

Subject: vomer
Value: the triangular flat bone of the nasal septum

Subject: manus
Value: distal segment of the fore limb, including carpal region, metacarpal region and digits.

Subject: pericardial sac
Value: a double-walled sac containing the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Subject: clitoris
Value: the small, erectile body located at the anterior end of the vulva

Subject: pars intermedia of adenohypophysis
Value: the thin boundary between the adenohypophysis and neurohypophysis of the pituitary that produces melanocyte stimulating hormone (MSH); this area is small or absent in mammalian adults

Subject: pituitary stalk
Value: the apical portion of the tubular structure extending from the hypothalamus to the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland

Subject: cervicothoracic ganglion
Value: the group of neurons formed by the fusion of the inferior cervical and first thoracic ganglia

Subject: ethmoid sinus
Value: the evaginations of the mucous membrane of the nasal cavity into the ethmoidal bony labyrinth, forming multiple small paranasal sinuses

Subject: orbitosphenoid
Value: the bone that is situated in the orbit on either side of the presphenoid; it generally forms a part of the sphenoid in the adult, and may be independent in the young

Subject: trabecular bone tissue
Value: bone tissue that has a lattice-like or spongy structure; it is highly vascular and contains intercommunicating spaces filled with bone marrow

Subject: bone marrow cavity
Value: the medullary cavities of the bones where bone marrow is stored

Subject: glottis
Value: the vocal apparatus of the larynx, which includes the vocal cords and the opening between them

Subject: tooth cavity
Value: the central hollow space of a tooth

Subject: coronal suture
Value: the dense, fibrous connective tissue joint between the tetrapod parietal bones and the frontal bone

Subject: lambdoid suture
Value: the dense, fibrous connective tissue joint between the parietal bones and the occipital bone

Subject: sagittal suture
Value: the dense, fibrous connective tissue joint between the tetrapod parietal bones

Subject: uterine artery
Value: the branch of the internal iliac artery that supplies the uterus and the upper part of the vagina

Subject: papillary muscle of heart
Value: one of the group of myocardial bundles which terminate in the chordae tendineae that attach to the cusps of the atrioventricular valves; each ventricle has an anterior and a posterior papillary muscle; the right ventricle sometimes has a septal papillary muscle

Subject: deltopectoral crest
Value: a rough elevation at the middle of the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus to which the deltoid muscle attaches

Subject: zygomatic arch
Value: the bony arch in vertebrates that extends along the side or front of the skull beneath the eye socket and is formed by the temporal process of the zygomatic bone and the zygomatic process of the temporal bone

Subject: oval window
Value: the oval opening on the medial wall of the tympanic cavity leading into the vestibule, close to the foot of the stapes

Subject: round window of inner ear
Value: the opening on the medial wall of the middle ear leading into the cochlea, closed in life by the secondary tympanic membrane; serves to regulate fluid pressure in the inner ear

Subject: celiac lymph node
Value: the visceral glands that are associated with the branches of the celiac artery, including the gastric, hepatic, and pancreaticolienal (splenic) lymph nodes

Subject: trabecula carnea
Value: the supporting bundles of muscular fibers lining the walls of the ventricles of the heart

Subject: periosteum
Value: the thick fibrous membrane that closely invests the entire surface of a bone except the articular cartilage at synovial joints

Subject: otolith organ
Value: the crystalline particles composed of calcium carbonate and a protein which adhere to the gelatinous membrane of the maculae of the utricle and saccule (otolithic membrane)

Subject: gland
Value: an organ that functions as a secretory or excretory organ

Subject: emboliform nucleus
Value: the small wedge shaped nucleus interposed between the dentate and fastigial nuclei; it receives axons from Purkinje cells of the intermediate area of the cerebral hemispheres and most of its efferent connections travel via the superior cerebellar peduncle

Subject: anterior nucleus of hypothalamus
Value: a loose heterogeneous collection of cells in the anterior hypothalamus, continuous rostrally with the medial and lateral preoptic areas and caudally with the tuber cinereum

Subject: supraoptic crest
Value: one of the circumventricular organs of the brain. The OVLT is outside the blood brain barrier, and so neurons in this region can respond to factors that are present in the systemic circulation.

Subject: decussation of trochlear nerve
Value: the crossing of the two trochlear nerves at their exit through the velum medullare anterius.

Subject: dorsal acoustic stria
Value: white matter structure containing fibers arising from the cochlear nuclear complex

Subject: vestibulocochlear ganglion
Value: the group of neuron cell bodies associated with the eighth cranial nerve during embryogenesis; splits in later development to form the cochlear and vestibular ganglia

Subject: chiasmatic cistern
Value: the region of the subarachnoid space that is located below and anterior to the optic chiasm

Subject: primitive knot
Value: organizer for gastrulation in vertebrates. The primitive knot starts as a regional knot of cells that forms on the blastodisc immediately anterior to where the outer layer of cells will begin to migrate inwards - an area known as the primitive streak. Posterior to the node is the primitive pit, where the cells of the epiblast (the upper layer of embryonic cells) initially begin to invaginate. This invagination expands posteriorly into the primitive groove as the cells layers continue to move into the space between the embryonic cells and the yolk. This differentiates the embryo into the germ layers - endoderm, mesoderm, and ectoderm. The primitive knot migrates posteriorly as gastrulation proceeds, eventually being absorbed into the tail bud.[WP]. the regional thickening of cells at the rostral tip of the vertebrate primitive streak through which gastrulating cells migrate anteriorally to form tissues in the future head and neck; this region organizes the formation of the three embryonic layers and establishes the longitudinal axis and the polarity of the embryo[MP].

Subject: optic stalk
Value: the narrow, proximal portion of the optic vesicle which connects the embryonic eye and forebrain

Subject: cranial neural crest
Value: neural crest cells (NCCs) originating in the anterior part of the developing embryo and residing between the mid-diencephalon and the forming hindbrain; cranial NCCs migrate dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various craniofacial cartilages and bones, cranial neurons, glia, and connective tissues of the face; these cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they give rise to thymic cells, bones of the middle ear and jaw (mandible), and the odontoblasts of the tooth primordia; like their counterparts in the trunk, cranial NCCs also contribute to the developing peripheral nervous system, along with the pigmented cell (i.e. melanocyte) lineage.

Subject: suspensorium
Value: (1) the arrangement of bones which supports the jaw from the braincase; (2) in teleost fish, a large, usually triangular, bone which supports the jaw. The teleost suspensorium is formed by fusion of various elements which vary among different taxa.

Subject: pharyngeal arch 4
Value: contributes to development of the cartilage of the larynx, laryngeal, pharyngeal, and soft palate muscles, superior parathyroid gland, and C-cells of the thymus

Subject: arthropod sternum
Value: ventral portion of a segment of an arthropod thorax or abdomen. In insects, the sterna are usually single, large sclerites, and external. However, they can sometimes be divided in two or more, in which case the subunits are called sternites, and may also be modified on the terminal abdominal segments so as to form part of the functional genitalia, in which case they are frequently reduced in size and development, and may become internalized and/or membranous.

Subject: blood nerve barrier
Value: barrier between the perineurium of peripheral nerves and the vascular endothelium of endoneurial capillaries. The perineurium acts as a diffusion barrier, but ion permeability at the blood-nerve barrier is still higher than at the blood-brain barrier[GO].

Subject: blood-cerebrospinal fluid barrier
Value: barrier in the choroid plexus located in the lateral, third, and fourth brain ventricles that controls the entrance of substances into the cerebrospinal fluid from the blood[MP].

Subject: alveolus
Value: organ part that has the form of a hollow cavity[WP].

Subject: metanephric mesenchyme
Value: one of the two embryological structures that give rise to the kidney (the other is the ureteric bud). The metanephric blastema mostly develops into nephrons, but can also form parts of the collecting duct system.[WP]. Metanephric mesenchyme is the tissue made up of loosely connected mesenchymal cells in the metanephros[GO]

Subject: epithelium of mammary gland
Value: the epithelial layer of the luminal surfaces of the mammary gland

Subject: roof plate of midbrain
Value: the mesencephalic roof plate, including the caudal and rostral part of the midbrain roof

Subject: smooth muscle of eye
Value: <any of the striated muscles that move the eye and include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, lateral rectus, superior oblique, inferior oblique, retractor bulbi>

Subject: small intestine Peyer's patch
Value: nodular lymphoid structures on the serosal surface of the small intestine.

Subject: trachea cartilage
Value: the ring-shaped cartilaginous structures that support the trachea

Subject: inguinal canal
Value: the passage in the lower abdominal wall through which the spermatic cord in the male or the round ligament in the female, nerves and vessels pass from the pelvic cavity to the scrotum or labia majora, respectively

Subject: sinus of Valsalva
Value: one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.

Subject: musculocutaneous nerve
Value: a large branch of the brachial plexus supplying various parts of the upper arm (as flexor muscles) and forearm (as the skin).

Subject: neural arch
Value: <posterior part of a vertebra that consists of a pair of pedicles and a pair of laminae, and supports seven processes: four articular processes, two transverse processes one spinous process[WP]. ZFA: A neural arch encloses the neural canal and typically meets its partner to form a neural spine. .>

Subject: hippocampal field
Value: a part or parts of the hippocampus that have a particular function

Subject: extraembryonic coelomic cavity
Value: the fluid-filled spaces formed within the mass of extraembryonic mesoderm that later fuse to become a large extraembryonic cavity

Subject: Mullerian duct
Value: paired ducts of the embryo that run down the lateral sides of the urogenital ridge and terminate at the mullerian eminence in the primitive urogenital sinus. In the female, they will develop to form the fallopian tubes, uterus, and the upper portion of the vagina; in the male, they are lost. These ducts are made of tissue of mesodermal origin[WP]. develops either by lengthwise splitting of the archinephric duct (in chondrichthyans and some amphibians) or by a elongated invagination of the coelomic epithelium (other vertebrates) In males, the oviducts regress. The cranial end of the oviduct maintains an opening into the coelom (which primitively may have been the anteriormost coelomic funnels connecting the nephrocoel with the coelom). This opening is the ostium tubae[USM].

Subject: sinusoid
Value: small blood vessel similar to a capillary but with a fenestrated endothelium. Sinusoids are found in the liver, lymphoid tissue, endocrine organs, and hematopoietic organs such as the bone marrow and the spleen. Sinusoids found within terminal villi of the placenta are not comparable to these; they possess a continuous endothelium and complete basal lamina[WP].

Subject: splenic sinusoid
Value: wide vessels in the spleen that drain into trabecular veins[WP].

Subject: tooth-like structure
Value: hard bony, calcareous, or chitinous organ found in the mouth or pharynx of an animal and used in procuring or masticating food.

Subject: pancreas primordium
Value: embryonic structure that develops into pancreatic bud.

Subject: dorsal pancreatic bud
Value: pancreatic bud that gives rise to the accessory pancreatic duct.

Subject: ventral pancreatic bud
Value: pancreatic bud that gives rise to the major pancreatic duct.

Subject: styloid process of temporal bone
Value: slender needle-like pointed projection that runs downward and slightly forward from the base of the inferior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone where it joins the tympanic portion; it gives attachment to the styloglossus, stylohyoid, and stylopharyngeus muscles and the stylohyoid and stylomandibular ligaments

Subject: prevertebral ganglion
Value: the sympathetic ganglia located in front of the vertebral column and are associated with the major branches of the abdominal aorta; these include the celiac, aorticorenal, superior and inferior mesenteric ganglia

Subject: gonial bone
Value: investing bone that lies on the surface of the malleus.

Subject: placental labyrinth vasculature
Value: blood vessels of the layer of the placenta where embryonic and maternal blood vessels interdigitate

Subject: primordial ovarian follicle
Value: primordial follicles are indiscernible to the naked eye and develop to primary, secondary, and finally mature vesicular follicles

Subject: hyoid bone lesser horn
Value: shorter and more medial of the paired processes on either side of the hyoid bone[MP]

Subject: cerebellum lobule
Value: one of the the ten gyri of the cerebellar cortex

Subject: head ectomesenchyme
Value: mesenchymal cells derived from neural crest cells that contribute to development of the hard and soft tissue in the head and neck, including the branchial arches[MP].

Subject: brain ventricle
Value: one of the system of communicating cavities in the brain that are continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord, that like it are derived from the medullary canal of the embryo, that are lined with an epithelial ependyma, and that contain a serous fluid

Subject: alveolar ridge
Value: one of the two jaw ridges either on the roof of the mouth between the upper teeth and the hard palate or on the bottom of the mouth behind the lower teeth[WP]. The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth[HP].

Subject: crus of ear
Value: horizontal piece of cartilage located outside the ear canal that divides the upper and lower parts of the ear.

Subject: tympanic cavity
Value: small cavity surrounding the bones of the middle ear.

Subject: myocardial compact layer
Value: outer dense layer of the myocardium uniting the epicardium and myocardium[MP].

Subject: growth plate cartilage
Value: cartilage that will provide a scaffold for mineralization of endochondral bones as they elongate or grow.

Subject: anterior ectodermal midgut
Value: portions of the midgut that are derived from ectoderm.

Subject: aorta smooth muscle tissue
Value: the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue located in the wall of the aorta

Subject: glomerular capillary
Value: the small branching blood vessels in the kidney glomerulus that receives blood from the kidney afferent arterioles; these capillaries are under high pressure for filtering within the glomerulus

Subject: kidney pelvis smooth muscle
Value: the smooth muscle tissue surrounding the urothelium of the kidney pelvis

Subject: blood vessel smooth muscle
Value: smooth muscle found within, and composing the majority of the wall of blood vessels.

Subject: trophectoderm
Value: outermost layer of cells in the blastodermic vesicle, which will develop into the trophoblast layer and then contact the endometrium and take part in establishing the embryo's means of nutrition

Subject: gubernaculum (male or female)
Value: embryonic structures which begin as undifferentiated mesenchyme attaching to the caudal end of the gonads. The gubernaculum is present only during the development of the urinary and reproductive organs, being replaced by distinct vestiges in males and females[WP]. Enitoinguinal ligaments that, in the male, connect the fetal testis to the developing scrotum, and, in the female, connect the ovaries to the uterus[MP]

Subject: apical ectodermal ridge
Value: multilayered ectodermal region at the distal tip of a limb or fin bud necessary for the proper development of the underlying mesenchyme[MP,modified]. Along with the zone of polarizing activity, it is a crucial organizing region during limb development[WP].

Subject: ectoplacental cone
Value: thickened trophoblast of the blastocyst in rodents that becomes the fetal portion of the placenta

Subject: vitelline blood vessel
Value: blood vessel that is connected to the yolk sac.

Subject: extraembryonic ectoderm
Value: layer of the endoderm of the extraembryonic tissue.

Subject: vitelline vasculature
Value: vascular network that is connected to the yolk sac.

Subject: tarsal region
Value: mesopodial segment of the pes, including the tarsal skeleton and associated tissues.

Subject: musculature of pharynx
Value: the collection of muscles that acts on the pharynx.

Subject: epididymis epithelium
Value: the layer of secretory cells which lines the epididymis

Subject: gastroesophageal sphincter
Value: the thick circular layer of smooth gastric musculature encircling the gastroesophageal junction that functions to reduce backflow into the esophagus from the stomach

Subject: renal afferent arteriole
Value: the blood vessels that branch from the kidney interlobular artery, convey blood to the glomerular capillaries, and play an important role in the regulation of blood pressure as a part of the tubuloglomerular feedback mechanism

Subject: renal efferent arteriole
Value: the blood vessels that convey blood from the glomerulocapillary network to the capillary bed of the proximal convoluted tubule

Subject: spleen capsule
Value: the connective tissue that surrounds the spleen

Subject: liver lobule
Value: the polygonal structure of the liver that consists of hepatocytes radiating outward from a hepatic vein

Subject: sphenoid bone pterygoid process
Value: the process projecting downward from either side of the sphenoid bone, in vertebrates divided into two plates, an inner and an outer (sometimes called the lateral and medial); the posterior nares pass through the space, called the pterygoid fossa, between the processes

Subject: scapula spine
Value: the triangular ridge on the dorsal aspect of the scapula which separates the supra- from the infraspinatous fossa and where the trapezius and deltoid muscles are attached

Subject: mandible condylar process
Value: articular part of the mandible bone

Subject: vertebra lamina
Value: two broad plates directed dorsomedially from the pedicles; these fuse at the dorsal midline, and complete the dorsal wall of the vertebral foramen

Subject: aorta tunica adventitia
Value: the outermost layer of the aorta wall, containing connective tissue and collagen and elastic fibers

Subject: spinal cord gray commissure
Value: the band of grey substance spanning the midline of the spinal cord that surrounds the central canal

Subject: gastro-splenic ligament
Value: peritoneum connecting the greater curvature of stomach with the hilum of the spleen[umich]. part of the greater omentum; derived from the dorsal mesogastrium in the embryo.

Subject: lieno-renal ligament
Value: peritoneum that attaches the spleen to the posterior abdominal wall over the left kidney. develops from the dorsal mesogastrium of the embryo[umich]

Subject: Peyer's patch epithelium
Value: the specialized epithelium of the Peyer's patch

Subject: bulbus cordis
Value: a transient fetal dilation of the distal (or cranial) heart tube located where the arterial trunk joins the ventral roots of the aortic arches

Subject: piriform cortex
Value: the subdivision of the laminated olfactory cortex with only three main layers that receive monosynaptic input from the olfactory bulb via the lateral olfactory tract; it is located bilaterally in the ventrolateral forebrain and is commonly divided into anterior and posterior regions

Subject: metanephric glomerulus
Value: glomerulus of the mature vertebrate kidney, or metanephros.

Subject: metanephric juxtaglomerular apparatus
Value: juxtaglomerular apparatus of the mature vertebrate kidney, or metanephros.

Subject: dermal skeletal element
Value: dermis-derived entity that is made of skeletal tissue.

Subject: respiratory system mucosa
Value: the mucous membrane lining the respiratory tract

Subject: kidney pelvis urothelium
Value: the epithelial lining of the luminal space of the kidney pelvis

Subject: thymus trabecula
Value: the thymic connective tissue which extends into the parenchyma

Subject: respiratory tract epithelium
Value: the pseudostratified ciliated epithelium that lines much of the conducting portion of the airway, including part of the nasal cavity and larynx, the trachea, and bronchi

Subject: nephron tubule epithelium
Value: the cellular avascular layer of the renal tubule luminar surfaces

Subject: seminiferous tubule epithelium
Value: the stratified epithelial lining of the seminiferous tubules, consisting of the developing spermatozoa and the supporting Sertoli cells, which are tall, columnar type cells that line the tubule

Subject: kidney epithelium
Value: the cellular avascular layer of the kidney luminar surfaces

Subject: aorta endothelium
Value: the thin layer of flat cells that line the aorta and form a barrier between circulating blood in the lumen and the rest of the vessel wall

Subject: distal visceral endoderm
Value: precursors of the anterior visceral endoderm that arises at the distal tip of the embryo[MP]

Subject: sphincter of hepatopancreatic ampulla
Value: muscular valve that controls the flow of digestive juices (bile and pancreatic juice) through the ampulla of Vater into the second part of the duodenum. Relaxed by the hormone Cholecystokinin (CCK) via vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP).[WP].

Subject: interstitial tissue
Value: connective tissue between the cellular elements of a structure.

Subject: trachea gland
Value: a tubuloacinar seromucous gland that is located principally in the submucosa of the trachea. Excretory ducts from this gland pass through the lamina propria to the tracheal lumen.

Subject: renal medulla interstitium
Value: tissue surrounding the loop of Henle in the renal medulla.

Subject: lobar bronchus of right lung cranial lobe
peritubular capillary
Value: the tiny blood vessels that receive blood from the efferent arterioles of the glomerulus, and interact with superficial cortical nephrons allowing reabsorption and secretion between blood and the inner lumen of the nephron; peritubular capillaries are situated around the tubule and are at low pressure

Subject: gonadal ridge
Value: the elevation of thickened mesothelium and underlying mesenchyme found on the ventromedial border of the embryonic mesonephros in which the primordial germ cells become embedded, establishing it as the primordium of the testis or ovary

Subject: ovary sex cord
Value: structures that develop from sex cords in the female. After further development they become the ovarian follicles.

Subject: submucous nerve plexus
Value: the gangliated plexus of unmyelinated nerve fibers that ramify the stomach and intestinal submucosa

Subject: malleus head
Value: rounded portion of the malleus that articulates with the body of the incus[MP].

Subject: brain ependyma
Value: the ependymal cell layer that lines the brain ventricles

Subject: spinal cord ependyma
Value: the ependymal cell layer that lines the spinal cord

Subject: vagus X ganglion
Value: the group of sensory neuron cell bodies associated with the vagus nerve

Subject: inferior vagus X ganglion
Value: the large group of sensory neuron cell bodies, anterior to the jugular vein, associated with the vagus nerve (tenth cranial nerve)

Subject: superior vagus X ganglion
Value: the upper ganglion of the vagus nerve located at the jugular foramen

Subject: spinal cord dorsal column
Value: the wedge-shaped fiber bundle of white matter in the dorsomedial side of the spinal cord that is made up of the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus; it is part of the ascending posterior column-medial lemniscus pathway that is important for well-localized fine touch and conscious proprioception

Subject: spinal cord lateral column
Value: the region of white matter of the spinal cord that is located between the dorsal and ventral spinal roots

Subject: spinal cord ventral column
Value: the area of white matter of the spinal cord located on either side of the ventral (anterior) medial fissure

Subject: olfactory bulb subependymal zone
Value: the region of mitotically active layer of cells surrounding the lateral brain ventricles that consists of migrating neuroblasts, astrocytes and transitory amplifying progenitor cells, that produce neurons that migrate to the olfactory bulb

Subject: philtrum
Value: the vertical groove found on the median line of the upper lip, extending to the nose

Subject: sublingual ganglion
Value: the small parasympathetic ganglion found anterior to the submandibular gland that provides postsynaptic fibers to the sublingual gland

Subject: bony otic capsule
Value: the cartilage or bony capsule surrounding the inner ear mechanism

Subject: coronary sinus
Value: the short trunk that recieves most of the cardiac veins carrying the blood from the myocardium and delivers it to the right atrium, with the sinoatrial connection occurring between the inferior vena cava and the atrioventricular orifice

Subject: spinal nerve trunk
Value: trunk part of spinal nerve, where dorsal and ventral roots meet to form the spinal nerve, before branching off to dorsal and ventral rami.

Subject: valve of inferior vena cava
Value: the semicircular fold of endocardium located on the right atrium at the point of attachment of the inferior vena cava; during development this valve helps direct the flow of oxygen-rich blood through the right atrium into the left cardiac atrium via the foramen ovale (preventing blood flowing into the right ventricle)

Subject: vitelline vein
Value: the paired veins that carry blood from the yolk sac back to the embryo

Subject: rhombomere 3
Value: the third transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 4
Value: the fourth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 5
Value: the fifth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 6
Value: the sixth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 7
Value: the seventh transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 8
Value: the eighth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: rhombomere 2
Value: the second transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

Subject: semi-lunar valve
Value: the valves that gate the flow of blood from the ventricles into the aorta and pulmonary trunk

Subject: primary vitreous
Value: embryonic fibrovascular mesodermal tissue located between the optic cup and lens vesicle that normally regresses during the development of the vitreous body[MP]

Subject: glomerular basement membrane
Value: the layer of extracellular matrix that lies between the endothelium of the glomerular capillaries and the podocytes of the inner or visceral layer of the Bowman capsule; it is a fusion of the endothelial cell and podocyte basal laminas and acts as a physical barrier and an ion-selective filter

Subject: mandibular prominence
Value: the paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip

Subject: maxillary prominence
Value: the paired dorsal prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo that unite with the ipsilateral medial nasal process to form the upper jaw

Subject: undifferentiated genital tubercle
Value: the embryonic anlage of the external genitalia, which emerges as paired swellings ventral to the cloacal membrane, is proposed to be derived from all three germ layers, and gives rise to the penis, clitoris, scrotum, labia, and foreskin

Subject: primary choana
Value: initial opening of the nasal pits and olfactory sac of the embryo into the rostral part of the primordial oronasal cavity, before the formation of the secondary palate.

Subject: brain commissure
Value: any of the nerve fiber tracts that span the longitudinal fissure between the cerebral and/or cerebellar hemispheres of the brain

Subject: pectineal ligament
Value: an extension of the lacunar ligament that runs on the pectineal line of the pubic bone.

Subject: bulbo-ventricular groove
Value: depression at base of developing heart that contains a population of cardiomyocytes that migrate and contribute to the interventricular septum

Subject: rhombic lip
Value: the posterior section of the developing metencephalon recognized transiently within the vertebrate embryo; the rhombic lip extends posteriorly from the roof of the fourth ventricle to dorsal neuroepithelial cell and can be divided into eight structural units based on rhombomeres 1-8 (r1-r8), recognized at early stages of hindbrain development; producing granule cells and five brainstem nuclei, the rhombic lip plays an important role in developing a complex cerebellar neural system

Subject: otic pit
Value: the pair of depressions of thickened otic placode epithelium, that further develops into the otic vesicles

Subject: early prosencephalic vesicle
Value: future brain vesicle that gives rise to telencephalic ventricle/lateral ventricles and 3rd ventricle

Subject: inferior oblique extraocular muscle
Value: thin, narrow muscle placed near the anterior margin of the floor of the orbit.

Subject: anterior lingual gland
Value: the small glands located near the apex of the tongue on either side of the frenulum

Subject: perihilar interstitium
Value: the part of the renal interstitium surrounding the pelvis

Subject: premacula segment of distal straight tubule
basisphenoid bone
Value: part of the base of the cranium between the basioccipital and the presphenoid, which usually ossifies separately in the embryo or in the young, and becomes a part of the sphenoid in the adult; in many animals it persists as a separate bone between the basioccipital bone and the presphenoidal bone

Subject: os penis
Value: the unique bone located in the glans penis of most mammals except humans; it is used for copulation and varies in size and shape by species

Subject: dorsal pes interosseous muscle
Value: the most superior muscles in the sole of the foot that abduct the second to fourth toes. These four muscles also act through the dorsal expansions to resist extension of the metatarsophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints.

Subject: crus of penis
Value: the continuation of each corpus cavernosum of the penis, diverging posteriorly to be attached to the pubic arch.

Subject: tunica albuginea of testis
Value: the dense fibrous connective tissue layer that covers the testis.

Subject: tunica vaginalis testis
Value: the outer coelomic epithelial covering of the testis; a sac of serous tissue covering the testis and the epididymis within which the testis can move about; it covers the tunica albuginea

Subject: septum of scrotum
Value: an incomplete wall of connective tissue and nonstriated muscle (dartos fascia) dividing the scrotum into two sacs, each containing a testis.

Subject: central tendon of diaphragm
Value: the three-lobed cloverleaf-shaped aponeurosis situated at the center of the diaphragm; the central tendon is fused with the fibrous pericardium that provides attachment for the muscle fibers

Subject: alisphenoid bone
Value: either of the broad curved wing like expanses on each side of the sphenoid bone in adults; may exist independently in the young

Subject: cochlear modiolus
Value: the central cone shaped core of spongy bone about which turns the spiral canal

Subject: liver perisinusoidal space
Value: the extravascular space in the liver between the parenchymal cells and a sinusoid that contains the blood plasma

Subject: corneo-scleral junction
Value: the edge of the cornea where it joins the sclera; the limbus is a common site for the occurrence of corneal epithelial neoplasm

Subject: long bone epiphyseal plate proliferative zone
Value: germinal layer of the epiphyseal plate where cells are actively dividing as well as producing extracellular matrix[MP].

Subject: long bone epiphyseal plate ossification zone
Value: layer of the epiphyseal plate where new bone matrix is deposited[MP].

Subject: annular epiphysis
Value: secondary growth centers occurring as rings at the periphery of the superior and inferior surfaces of the vertebral body.

Subject: tectal plate
Value: embryologic structure that is formed by two longitudinal eminences, one on each alar plate of the midbrain. These eminences become the superior colliculus and inferior colliculus ( Carpenter-1983 )]

Subject: superficial white layer of superior colliculus
Value: superficial white matter layer of superior collilculus that consists mainly of axions from the optic nerve.

Subject: deep white layer of superior colliculus
Value: deep white matter layer of superior collilculus that consists entirely of fibers.

Subject: remnant of left anterior vena cava
embryonic footplate
Value: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the pes (foot)

Subject: embryonic handplate
Value: the distal elements of the developing limb of vertebrates that will give rise to the manus (hand)

Subject: stomach glandular region mucosa
Value: stomach mucosa that is lined with glandular epithelium and part of a stomach glandular region.

Subject: thymus subcapsular epithelium
Value: the epithelial cells lining the capsule and trabeculae of the thymus

Subject: inner ear epithelium
Value: the epithelial cell layer containing the sensory hair cells and their associated sensory nerve terminals

Subject: mammary gland myoepithelium
