Value: the outer cell layer of the mammary gland epithelium bilayer which is located basal to the luminal (secretory) cells and adjacent to the basement membrane.

Subject: hermaphroditic organism
Value: multicellular organism that can produce both male and female gametes.

Subject: lingual tonsil
Value: the lymph tissue on the floor of the oropharyngeal passage, near the root of the tongue

Subject: rhamphotheca
Value: thin keratinized layer of epidermis projecting from outer surface of beak[WP].

Subject: stria vascularis vasculature
Value: blood vessels supplying the stria vascularis in the cochlea of the inner ear.

Subject: cerebellar peduncle
Value: any of the three large paired bundles of nerve fibers that connect the cerebellum to the brain stem

Subject: pigment epithelium of eye
Value: epithelial layer of the retina, ciliary body, or iris composed of cells containing pigment granules.

Subject: uriniferous tubule
Value: functional unit of the kidney that forms urine, consisting of two parts, the nephron and the collecting tubule.

Subject: kidney field
Value: region of the embryo into the area in which the kidney rudiment will develop.

Subject: thyroid diverticulum
Value: endodermal bud derived from the endodermal epithelium of the embryonic pharyngeal floor[MP]. The thyroid diverticulum is the embryological structure from which thyroid follicular cells derive. It grows from the floor of the pharnyx[WP].

Subject: accessory nasal cartilage
Value: small cartilages of the nose connecting the greater alar cartilage and lateral nasal cartilage.

Subject: osseus semicircular canal
Value: the organ of balance composed of three long bony tubes of the labyrinth

Subject: erectile tissue
Value: with numerous vascular spaces that may become engorged with blood

Subject: ceratoglossus
Value: main, posterior part of hyoglossus muscle (vs. chondroglossus) arising from the greater horn of the hyoid bone.

Subject: parietal endoderm
Value: primitive endoderm-derived tissue that lines the luminal surface of the mural trophectoderm[MP]

Subject: prostate gland dorsolateral lobe
Value: the rodent prostate lobe that lies in the triangular area between urethra and seminal vesicle

Subject: hemipenis
Value: one of a pair of intromittent organs of male squamates. Hemipenes are usually held inverted, within the body, and are everted for reproduction via erectile tissue like that in the human penis. Only one is used at a time, and some evidence indicates males alternate use between copulations. The hemipenis itself has a variety of shapes, depending on species. Often the hemipenis bears spines or hooks, in order to anchor the male within the female. Some species even have forked hemipenes (each hemipenis has two tips). Due to being everted and inverted, hemipenes do not have a completely enclosed channel for the conduction of sperm, but rather a seminal groove which seals as the erectile tissue expands

Subject: pulmonary surfactant
Value: a substance formed by type II alveolar cells composed of surface-active lipoprotein complex (phospholipoprotein).

Subject: cerebellum external granule cell layer
Value: transient layer of the cerebellar cortex present during development which is composed of dividing and migrating granule cells[MP]

Subject: ectoplacental cavity
Value: closed space within the ectoplacental cone, formed by the fusion of the parts of the amniotic fold that separate it from the amniotic cavity[MP]. a developmental cavity that exists in some mammals and is derived by division of the proamniotic space; it is further removed from the embryo than the amniotic cavity in some mammals

Subject: visceral yolk sac
Value: extraembryonic tissue membrane, formed from the visceral endoderm and the extraembryonic mesoderm, which is located ventral to the embryonic disc and is connected to the presumptive midgut of the embryo; the yolk that it contains is the site of embryonic hematopoiesis and vitelline circulation is involved in early embryonic circulation; it is the origin of the primordial germ cells

Subject: parietal yolk sac
Value: tissue that consists of two cellular layers (parietal endoderm and trophoblast) separated by a relatively thick nonvascular basement membrane (Reichert's membrane), and acts as a protective layer to supports and facilitates transport of nutrients between the uterine tissue and the yolk sac cavity.

Subject: primary somatosensory cortex
Value: <(Chapin & Lin, 1984, rat): the region considered as the SI cortex is not a cytoarchitecturally homogeneous structure but consists instead of a patchwork array of areas containing dense aggregations of layer IV granule cells, surrounded by granule-cell-sparse regions. As was shown by Welker (b71,b76), and in our own mapping studies (see Fig. 3), this discontinuous pattern of granular, or koniocortical, zones contains within itself a map of the ratbs cutaneous periphery. There are clear subtypes within this cytoarchitectural subregion, notably including the bgranular aggregateb type of cytoarchitecture characteristic of the paw, limb, and mystacial vibrissae areas, and the bbarrel-fieldb type (originally described by Woolsey and Van der Loos, b70) seen in the nose and perioral regions. In the mouse, but not the rat, such barrels also cover the whole whisker representation (Welker and Woolsey, b74).>

Subject: secondary somatosensory cortex
Value: the area of the upper bank of the lateral sulcus that is involved in somatic sensation

Subject: parabronchus
Value: tertiary bronchus in the avian lung.

Subject: apocrine gland
Value: any exocrine gland whose cells bud their secretions off through the plasma membrane producing membrane-bound vesicles in the lumen; the apical portion of the secretory cell of the gland pinches off and enters the lumen; it loses part of its cytoplasm in their secretions; apocrine secretion is functional during hormonal stress or puberty; an example of true apocrine glands are mammary glands, responsible for secreting breast milk.

Subject: white fibrocartilage
Value: fibrocartilage in which strong bundles of white fibrous tissue predominate.

Subject: syrinx organ
Value: vocal organ of birds, located at the base of a trachea

Subject: foramen primum
Value: opening in the septum primum between the two atria of the embryonic heart[TMD].

Subject: parapodium
Value: either of a pair of fleshy lateral processes borne by most segments of a polychaete worm.

Subject: hypophyseal cartilage
Value: forms around the developing pituitary, and together with prechordal cartilages creates body of sphenoid bone

Subject: tunicate siphon
Value: tubular appendage for drawing or ejecting fluids

Subject: spermaceti
Value: wax present in the head cavities of the sperm whale.

Subject: tadpole stage
Value: <wholly aquatic larval stage in the life cycle of an amphibian, particularly of a frog or toad[WP]. XAO: The stages from feeding to the end of metamorphosis. Encompasses Weisz's first-form tadpole (equivalent to NF stages 45 to 49), second-form tadpole (NF 49 to 56) and third-form tadpole (NF 56 to 60-plus) stages.>

Subject: echinoderm gastric caecum
Value: non-contractile pouch that is connected to the anterior stomach through a slit-like opening. This pouch is also well-connected to the haemal system through numerous haemal ducts within its connective tissue layer.

Subject: nephrogenic zone
Value: outer portion of the renal cortex. Site of formation of medullary and cortical elements.

Subject: anterior intestinal portal
Value: opening of the foregut into the midgut

Subject: principal gastric gland
Value: one of the gastric glands that secretes the hydrochloric acid of the gastric juice[Stedman's].

Subject: pulmonary neuroendocrine body
Value: corpuscular, organoid structures composed of PNECs, found as distinctive innervated clusters only within intrapulmonary airways, where they appear concentrated at airway branch points; NEBs reach from the basement membrane to the airway lumen and are thought to function as oxygen sensors.

Subject: neuroendocrine gland
Value: any of the organized aggregations of cells that function as secretory or excretory organs and that release hormones in response to neural stimuli

Subject: paraurethral gland
Value: the numerous mucous-secreting glands found in several female mammalian species (including rodents and humans) on the anterior wall of the vagina, around the lower end of the urethra, and possessing a common paraurethral duct which opens (on each side) near the external urethral orifice; they are homologous with the prostate gland in males, have highly variable anatomy, and are believed to be the source of the female ejaculate, a lubricating fluid with a similar consistency to male prostatic fluid that is expelled through the urethra during sexual stimulation; like the male prostate, these glands are susceptible to infection (skenitis), cyst development, and cancer

Subject: parietomastoid suture
Value: <unites the mastoid process of the temporal with the region of the mastoid angle of the parietal[WP:Squamosal_suture].>

Subject: moustache
Value: facial hair grown on the outer surface of the upper lip. It may or may not be accompanied by a type of beard, a facial hair style grown and cropped to cover most of the lower half of the face.

Subject: male urethral gland
Value: any of the numerous small mucous-secreting glands located in the wall of the penile urethra

Subject: pair of dorsal aortae
Value: the paired arterial structures of the embryo that supplies each developing somite via efferent segmental arteries; the dorsal aortae articulate with the umbilical arteries, which return mixed blood to the villi of the chorion for reoxygenation

Subject: arytenoid swellings
Value: paired primordial elevations, on either side of the embryonic larynx, within which the arytenoid cartilages are formed

Subject: anterior buccal gland
Value: the racemose, mucous or serous glands in the submucous tissue of the cheeks

Subject: nictitating membrane lamina
Value: thin cartilage element that stiffens the nictitating membrane.

Subject: optic pedicel
Value: permanent cartilage structure projecting from the site of origin of the recti muscles. Supports eyeball and aids rotation.

Subject: enteric nerve
Value: the neurons that innervate the esophagus, stomach, small and large bowel

Subject: spleen trabecular artery
Value: one of the branches of the splenic artery[MP]

Subject: spleen trabecular vein
Value: one of the veins that feed the splenic vein

Subject: cholinergic enteric nerve
Value: nerve fibers that utilize acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter to the intestinal system

Subject: inguinal fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue found in the groin

Subject: retroperitoneal fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue found on the dorsal side of the peritoneum

Subject: epididymal fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the epididymis

Subject: parametrial fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the extension of the subserous coat of the uterus laterally between the layers of the broad ligament

Subject: omental fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the fold of peritoneal tissue that extends from the stomach to the posterior abdominal wall after associating with the transverse colon

Subject: vibrissa follicle
Value: one of the tubular invaginations of the epidermis enclosing the hair roots and from which grow the vibrissae located on the muzzle and face of many species

Subject: oropharyngeal choana
Value: opening/conduit between the nasal cavity and the oropharynx via the roof of the mouth.

Subject: distal carpal bone 5
Value: endochondral carpal bone similar to distal carpal 4, but lost in most reptiles and mammals.

Subject: equine distal sesamoid
Value: lies on the palmar aspect of the coffin joint between the second phalanx and third phalanx. articulates closely with the distal phalanx, to which it is connected by the impar ligament of the navicular bone. The impar ligament is very strong and permits relatively little motion between the navicular bone and the distal phalanx.

Subject: ectethmoid
Value: either of two lateral parts of the ethmoid bone that form part of the anterior wall of the orbit

Subject: parafibula
Value: third bone of the lower leg, normally restricted to the area of the knee, in multuberculates, monotremes and some therians

Subject: thyroepiglotticus muscle
Value: fibers of the thyroarytenoid muscle that continue to the margin of the epiglottis; it closes the inlet to the larynx.

Subject: jugulohyoideus muscle
Value: runs from the processus jugularis to the os stylohyoideum; innervated with the ramus jugulohyoideus from the nervus facialis

Subject: endolymphatic space
Value: endolymph-filled space contained by the membranous labyrinth.

Subject: ligament of vertebral column
Value: ligament that joins successive centra. Important in controlling the stiffness of the vertebral column when it flexes.

Subject: Krause's gland
Value: small, mucous accessory lacrimal glands that are found underneath the eyelid where the upper and lower conjuctivae meet. Their ducts unite into a rather long sinus which open into the fornix conjunctiva. There are approximately forty Krause glands in the region of the upper eyelid, and around 6 to 8 in the region of the lower lid. The function of these glands are to produce tears which are secreted onto the surface of the conjuctiva

Subject: masseteric fossa
Value: .The fossa for the masseter. In some therapsids, the coronoid process of the dentary bears a large external depression which accommodates the masseter -- an important muscle in closing and in grinding motions of the jaw.

Subject: supraorbital ridge
Value: the superior half of the orbital rim, which constitutes the curved superior border of the orbital opening, formed by the frontal bone.

Subject: yolk sac blood island
Value: masses of developing blood cells attached to endothelium in the yolk sac

Subject: umbilical cord blood
Value: blood that remains in the placenta and in the attached umbilical cord after childbirth[WP].

Subject: ureteric bud trunk
Value: ureteric bud cells that elongate to form a rigid structure (stalk) consisting of polarized epithelial cells without branching; the stalks differentiate into the collecting system of the mature kidney, while the tip cells interact with the adjacent cells of the metanephric mesenchyme, inducing their conversion into nephrons.

Subject: urinary bladder vasculature
Value: network of tubes that carries blood through the distensible musculomembranous organ that serves to collect and store urine excreted by the kidneys[MP]

Subject: urethral meatus
Value: external opening or orifice of the urethra through which urine and seminal fluid (in males only) leave the body; in males the meatus presents as a vertical slit normally positioned at the tip of glans penis; in females the meatus is located between the clitoris and the vagina in the vulvular vestibule of the female genitalia[MP].

Subject: internal urethral orifice
Value: the usually crescent-shaped opening of the urinary bladder into the urethra, placed at the anteroinferior angle (apex) of the urinary bladder trigone

Subject: cervical gland
Value: mucus-secreting glands in the mucosa of the uterine cervix

Subject: forestomach-glandular stomach junction
Value: the distinct low fold of tissue that separates the non-glandular area of the stomach (forestomach) from the glandular stomach; the limiting ridge extends circumferentially from the large curvature of the stomach to the small curvature, just below the esophagus; at the esophagus, the course of the limiting ridge bends into a U-shape and almost surrounds the esophageal opening

Subject: mammary fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the mammary gland

Subject: femoral fat pad
Value: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the femur

Subject: male urethral crest
Value: narrow longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the male urethra, extending from the uvula of the bladder through the prostatic urethra; when distended, it may serve to prevent the passage of the semen backward into the bladder; on either side of the male urethral crest is a slightly depressed fossa, the prostatic sinus, the floor of which is perforated by the orifices of the prostatic ducts from the lateral lobes of the prostate; the ducts of the middle lobe open behind the crest; at the forepart of the crest, below its summit, is a median elevation, the colliculus seminalis, upon or within the margins of which are the orifices of the prostatic utricle and the slit-like openings of the ejaculatory ducts[MP]

Subject: male membranous urethra
Value: the shortest, least dilatable, and, with the exception of the external orifice, the narrowest part of the male urethral canal located in the deep perineal pouch and lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium; it extends downward and forward, with a slight anterior concavity, between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the urethra, perforating the urogenital diaphragm below and behind the pubic symphysis; the membranous portion of the urethra is completely surrounded by the fibers of the sphincter urethrae membranaceae; on either side near its termination are the bulbourethral glands

Subject: pearly penile papule
Value: small saliences on the ridge of the glans of the male genital organs.

Subject: holocrine gland
Value: any exocrine gland whose secretion consists of its own disintegrated secretory cells along with its secretory product; holocrine secretions are produced in the cytoplasm of the cell and released by the rupture of the plasma membrane, which destroys the cell and results in the secretion of the product into the lumen.

Subject: autopod pad
Value: pigmented, keratinised, hairless epidermis covering subcutaneous, collagenous, and adipose tissue.

Subject: colloid of thyroid follicle
Value: portion of substance contained within the thyroid follicle lumen. Contains prohormone thyroglobulin.

Subject: obsolete cloacal spur
Value: retained pelvic vestiges found in birds. They are generally used in courtship and are more pronounced in males than females.

Subject: Merkel nerve ending
Value: mechanoreceptors found in the skin and mucosa of vertebrates that provide touch information to the brain. The information they provide are those regarding pressure and texture. Each ending consists of a Merkel cell in close apposition with an enlarged nerve terminal

Subject: antler velvet
Value: highly vascular skin called velvet that covers the antler whilst it grows, supplying oxygen and nutrients to the growing bone.

Subject: ovarian cortex
Value: the layer of the ovarian stroma lying immediately beneath the tunica albuginea, composed of connective tissue cells and fibers, among which are scattered primary and secondary (antral) follicles in various stages of development; the cortex varies in thickness according to the age of the individual, becoming thinner with advancing years; included in the follicles are the cumulus oophorus, membrana granulosa (and the granulosa cells inside it), corona radiata, zona pellucida, and primary oocyte; the zona pellucida, theca of follicle, antrum and liquor folliculi are also contained in the follicle; also in the cortex is the corpus luteum derived from the follicles.

Subject: ovarian medulla
Value: highly vascular stroma found in the center of the ovary that forms from embryonic mesenchyme and contains blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves; this stroma forms the tissue of the hilum by which the ovarian ligament is attached, and through which the blood vessels enter; it does not contain any ovarian follicles.

Subject: sinovaginal bulb
Value: solid evaginations of the UG sinus that develops into a vaginal plate that which will will eventually canalize to form the inferior portion of the vagina.

Subject: remnnant of ductus deferens
Value: remnant in a female of the portion of the embryonic mesonephric duct that develops into the ductus deferens in males.

Subject: remnant of processus vaginalis
Value: incompletely obliterated remnants of the vaginal process of the peritoneum remaining in the spermatic cord.

Subject: dorsal gray commissure of spinal cord
Value: the part of the gray commissure in the spinal central gray posterior to the central canal of the spinal cord

Subject: striated duct of salivary gland
Value: gland duct which connects an intercalated duct to an interlobular duct in a salivary gland.

Subject: transverse cloacal muscle
Value: a very prominent superficial muscle and with its almost transverse course it forms the boundary between the abdomen and the tail.

Subject: levator cloacae
Value: a long narrow muscle arising from the underside of feather bulge of the lateral rectrices, inserting near the midline of the cloacal tubercle - phallus.

Subject: cerebral cortex marginal layer
Value: developing superficial cortical layer located just under the pia matter, develops from the marginal layer of the neural tube and becomes cortical layer I

Subject: choledocho-duodenal junction
Value: hat part of the duodenal wall traversed by the ductus choledochus, ductus pancreaticus, and ampulla.

Subject: pancreaticosplenic lymph node
Value: lymph nodes of the pancreatic tail and spleen, receiving afferents from both organs plus the greater curvature of the stomach; they drain to the celiac lymph nodes.

Subject: median palatine suture
Value: the line of junction between the horizontal parts of the palatine bones that extends from both sides of the skull to form the posterior part of the hard palate.

Subject: posterior pole of lens
Value: the central point on the posterior surface of the lens.

Subject: auditory system
Value: is the sensory system for the sense of hearing.

Subject: cavity of left atrium
Value: luminal space of the left atrium of the heart.

Subject: cavity of left ventricle
Value: luminal space of the left ventricle of the heart.

Subject: cavity of right atrium
Value: luminal space of the right atrium of the heart.

Subject: phlegm
Value: mucus produced in the respiratory tract.

Subject: nucleus of phrenic nerve
Value: neuron cell bodies located in the more medial portions of the anterior horn at cervical levels C3-C7 that innervate the diaphragm via the phrenic nerve.

Subject: pseudoclasper
Value: one or more pairs of stiff ossified lobes or prongs found in the tip of the intromittent organ of Bythitoidei

Subject: external thoracic vein
Value: extension of the long thoracic vein that collects blood from the mammary glands

Subject: internal surface of cranial base
Value: internal (endosteal) surface of the base of skull

Subject: upper canine 1
Value: first canine (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

Subject: upper molar 1
Value: first molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

Subject: bicipital surface
Value: region of the humerus associated with the biceps attachment areas

Subject: bulge
Value: expanded and swollen region of a surface that is otherwise relatively flat

Subject: caudal melanophore spot
Value: distinct colored area on the caudal region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.

Subject: choanal groove
Value: grooves on the palatine bone which denote the passage of the choana or internal naris

Subject: fourth phalanx
Value: fourth most proximal phalanx in manual or pedal digits.

Subject: jugal bar
Value: elongate bar consisting of fused quadratojugal and jugal and connecting the maxilla to the quadrate

Subject: midbody melanophore spot
Value: distinct colored area on the midbody region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.

Subject: prismatic cartilage
Value: <cartilage arranged into tesserae, blocks of calcified cartilage that fit together as tiles on a floor form a mosaic. Found only in chondrichthyans. Reference: A. Peter Klimley. 2013. The Biology of Sharks and Rays. University of Chicago Press.>

Subject: supratendinal bridge
Value: <ossified bridge over a tendon; Particularly, the bridge over the extensor canal at the distal end of the tibiotarsus of certain birds. The presence of the bridge and the position of the canal opening relative to the condyles may have phylogenetic significance. Ericson (1997). http://palaeos.com/vertebrates/glossary/glossarySq.html>

Subject: upper lateral line
Value: dorsal sensory canal line in fish, dorsal to ventral lateral lane

Subject: ventral lateral line
Value: ventral sensory canal line in fish, ventral to dorsal lateral lane

Subject: ventral supracondylar tubercle
Value: tubercle on the distal humerus for the origin of the Lig. collaterale ventral of the elbow joint. Modified from Baumel et al. 1993

Subject: dorsal supracondylar tubercle
Value: tubercle on the dorsal border of the distal humerus, a short distance from the dorsal epicondyle, for the origin of the m extensor carpe radialis modifeid from Baumel et al. 1993

Subject: low-pressure baroreceptor
Value: found in large systemic veins, in pulmonary vessels, and in the walls of the right atrium and ventricles of the heart (the atrial volume receptors).

Subject: lacteal
Value: a lymphatic capillary that absorbs dietary fats in the villi of the small intestine.

Subject: crus of penis or clitoris
Value: the continuation of each corpus cavernosum of the penis or clitoris, diverging posteriorly to be attached to the pubic arch.

Subject: neck of bone element
Value: the neck region of a bone organ.

Subject: anterior pole of lens
Value: the central point on the anterior surface of the lens.

Subject: meibum
Value: an oily substance that prevents evaporation of the eye's tear film

Subject: lacrimal gland bud
Value: <the single bud-like invagination of the conjunctival fornix epithelium at the temporal aspect of the eye that signals lacrimal gland formation (Int Rev Cytol. 1996;168:1-80. Cell biology of the harderian gland)>

Subject: strand of tylotrich hair
Value: <a single large hair, surrounded by neurovascular tissue at the level of the sebaceous gland, with a hair follicle innervated by a hair-tylotrich neuron (CL:1001436), a rapidly acting mechanoreceptor.>

Subject: pontocerebellar tract
Value: the second order neuron fibers of the corticopontocerebellar tracts that cross to the other side of the pons and run within the middle cerebellar peduncles, from the pons to the contralateral cerebellum.

Subject: temporoparietal junction
Value: an area of the brain that locates at the interception of temporal and parietal cortices (at the posterior end of the Sylvian fissure).

Subject: histaminergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to histamine.

Subject: catecholamine system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to the catecholamines.

Subject: gABAergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to GABA.

Subject: glutamatergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to glutamate (when in the role of a neurotransmitter).

Subject: serotonergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to serotonin.

Subject: cholinergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to acetylcholine.

Subject: adrenergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to epinephrine (also known as adrenaline).

Subject: noradrenergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to norepinephrine (also known as noradrenaline).

Subject: dopaminergic system
Value: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to dopamine.

Subject: spiral prominence of cochlear duct
Value: a projecting portion of the spiral ligament of the cochlea, bounding the lower edge of the stria vascularis and containing within it a blood vessel, the vas prominens.

Subject: yellow fibrocartilage
Value: fibrocartilage containing bundles of yellow elastic fibers but with little or no white fibrous tissue.

Subject: margin of eyelid
Value: the confluence of the mucosal surface of the conjunctiva, the edge of the orbicularis, and the cutaneous epithelium.

Subject: future neurohypophysis
Value: the outgrowth of neuroectoderm located on the floor of the embryonic hypothalamus that gives rise to the neurohypophysis (posterior lobe) of the pituitary gland

Subject: angioblastic cord
Value: the cordlike masses of splanchnic mesenchymal cells ventral to the primordial pericardial coelom that arrange themselves side by side to form the primordia of the endocardial heart tubes

Subject: prechordal mesoderm
Value: the area of axial mesoderm that develops into the prechordal plate

Subject: saccus vasculosus
Value: a circumventricular organ of the hypothalamus of many jawed fishes, protruding from the caudal infundibular wall. It is a vascularized neuroepithelium that consists of coronet cells, cerebrospinal fluid-contacting neurons and supporting cells.

Subject: aortic body
Value: one of several small clusters of chemoreceptors, baroreceptors, and supporting cells located along the aortic arch.

Subject: parotid gland myoepithelium
Value: epithelium that consists of stellate-shaped contractile cells with long dendritic processes that surround the secretory acini and intercalated ducts of the parotid gland, usually found in the glandular epithelium as a thin layer above the basement membrane but generally beneath the luminal cells; they display features of both smooth muscle and epithelium, such as numerous microfilaments with focal densities in the cytoplasmic processes, and desmosomes which attach them to the epithelial cells; their functions include contraction when the gland is stimulated to secrete, compressing or reinforcing the underlying parenchymal cells, thus aiding in the expulsion of saliva and preventing damage to the other cells

Subject: fauces
Value: lateral walls of the oropharynx that are located medial to the palatoglossal folds

Subject: interincisive suture
Value: median palatine suture of the palatine processes of the maxillary bones, and the median suture of the palatine bones

Subject: palatomaxillary suture
Value: line of union, in the floor of the orbit, between the orbital process of the palatine bone and the orbital surface of the maxilla.

Subject: transverse palatine suture
Value: the line of junction between the processes of the maxilla and the horizontal parts of the palatine bones that form the hard palate.

Subject: preputial space
Value: space between the prepuce and glans penis or clitoris

Subject: urogenital diaphragm
Value: muscular components of the deep perineal pouch.

Subject: gastrophrenic ligament
Value: the portion of the greater omentum that extends from the greater curvature of the stomach to the inferior surface of the diaphragm

Subject: outer root sheath companion layer
Value: the innermost layer of the outer root sheath.

Subject: left adrenal gland cortex
Value: the thick outer layer of the adrenal gland that is in the left side of the abdomen

Subject: left adrenal gland medulla
Value: the adrenal gland medulla that is in the left side of the abdomen

Subject: right adrenal gland cortex
Value: the thick outer layer of the adrenal gland that is in the right side of the abdomen

Subject: right adrenal gland medulla
Value: the adrenal gland medulla that is in the right side of the abdomen

Subject: esophagogastric junction mucosa
Value: mucosa from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

Subject: esophagogastric junction submucosa
Value: submucosa from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

Subject: esophagogastric junction muscularis mucosa
Value: muscularis mucosa from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

Subject: esophagogastric junction muscularis propria
Value: muscularis propria from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

Subject: orbital margin
Value: the mostly sharp edge of the orbital opening that is the peripheral border of the base of the pyramidal orbit.

Subject: sphenomaxillary suture
Value: an inconstant suture between the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone and the body of the maxilla.

Subject: Meyer's loop of optic radiation
Value: part of the optic radiation which sweeps back on itself into the temporal lobe, just lateral to the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle.

Subject: amiculum
Value: a dense surrounding coat of white fibers, as the sheath of the inferior olive and of the dentate nucleus.

Subject: obsolete proboscis
Value: <1: The trunk of an elephant; also: any long flexible snout. 2: Any of various elongated or extensible tubular processes as the sucking organ of a butterfly of the oral region of an invertebrate.>

Subject: interanterodorsal nucleus of the thalamus
Value: a group of nerve cells that bridges the midline of the thalamus between the anterodorsal nucleus of the thalamus of the left and right sides. According to Crosby (1962), it is more developed and consistently present in rodents than in primates (adapted from Brain Info).

Subject: bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract
Value: a group of cells near the surface of the brain between the supraoptic nucleus and the cortical amygdalar nucleus in the rat ( Swanson-1998 ) and the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ). It is one of five subdivisions of the medial amygdalar nucleus.

Subject: dopaminergic cell groups
Value: collections of neurons in the central nervous system that have been demonstrated by histochemical fluorescence to contain the neurotransmitter dopamine ( Fuxe-1970 )

Subject: incisive duct
Value: an infrequent rudimentary duct, or protrusion of the mucous membrane into the incisive canal, on either side of the anterior extremity of the nasal crest

Subject: glymphatic system
Value: macroscopic waste clearance system that utilizes a unique system of perivascular tunnels, formed by astroglial cells, to promote efficient elimination of soluble proteins and metabolites from the central nervous system.

Subject: ambient gyrus
Value: a rostral part of the parahippocampal gyrus.

Subject: incudostapedial joint
Value: the small synovial joint connecting the inclus and the stapes, located between the lenticular process on the long crus of the incus and the head of the stapes.

Subject: incudomallear joint
Value: the saddle-shaped synovial joint connecting the incus and the malleus.

Subject: epihyoideum
Value: an elastic ligament lying between the lateral pharyngeal muscles and the thyroglossus muscle

Subject: wall of heart
Value: wall of organ which has as its parts the endocardium, myocardium , epicardium, and the cardiac septum, surrounded by the pericardial sac proper and is continuous with the walls of the systemic and pulmonary arterial and venous trees.

Value: < The region of the upper jaw on or near the midline. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]>

Subject: anlage in statu nascendi
Value: <\"anlagen in statu nascendi\" are domains that do not yet coincide 1:1 with a later organ. Anlagen in statu nascendi are typically defined for the early blastoderm by the expression domains of genes which, in the late blastoderm or later, are expressed in specific anlagen, but initially come on in larger domains.>
